Changed my approach completely on this question in the past couple days. I started out looking at average quakes > 5.0 per day for a long period of time 27 years. However, the reason there have been so few MTD has been there have been no large earthquakes (call that >7.0) Oct or late-Sep.

the below comes with the caveat that i may have calculated the instances of zero- and one-earthquake-per-day wrong (i do not know much of anything about using data)... but playing around with a few thousand earthquake reports from 2002-2011 seemed to indicate that about 95% of the time, there are fewer than 12 earthquakes per day. it looks like a lognormal distribution. There's a 75% chance you won't see 10 earthquakes in a day given 15 days; a 50% chance you won't see 9 in a day given 15 days, etc.

Number of quakes over the past twenty years per month: (4%, 63%, 22%, 11%, 0%) is base rate. The average number for past twenty years is 138. The average number is 138 during the same time frame. Regression puts 2017 at ~ 152 w/ .16 r2. September there were 143. with 76 at half way point. Currently less than half at halfway point. See no reason to change rates.

Given my daily average and 42 earthquakes to date in October: We need 4 per day to get 103 (slightly below average daily) We need 6.7 per day to get >142 We need 8.9 per day to get >176 We need 11.5 per day to get >214

After 15 days in October, there have been just 41 earthquakes of magnitude 5.0 and above. averaging less than 3 per day. In the next 16 days, there would have to be more than 61 to reach the 103-142 bracket, and more than 102 to reach 142-176. I'm going to discount the higher two options now, as there would have to be an average of more than 8 per day to reach 176-214, and more than 11 per day to get to 215. Nature doesn't follow averages, but this is as good a strategy as any.
